# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tensorrt-llm
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] CUDA is both a software layer that manages data, giving direct access to the GPU and CPU as necessary, and a library of APIs that enable parallel computation for various needs.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] In addition to drivers and runtime kernels, the CUDA platform includes compilers, libraries and developer tools to help programmers accelerate their applications.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] CUDA is written in the C programming language but is designed to work with a wide array of other programming languages including C++, Fortran, Python and Julia.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] This accessibility makes it easier for specialists in parallel programming to use GPU resources, in contrast to prior APIs like Direct3D and OpenGL, which require advanced skills in graphics programming.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] CUDA-powered GPUs also support programming frameworks such as OpenMP, OpenACC and OpenCL.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] The graphics processing unit (GPU), as a specialized computer processor, addresses the demands of real-time high-resolution 3D graphics compute-intensive tasks.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] By 2012, GPUs had evolved into highly parallel multi-core systems allowing efficient manipulation of large blocks of data.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] The origins of CUDA trace to the early 2000s, when Ian Buck, a computer science Ph.D. student at Stanford University, began experimenting with using GPUs for purposes beyond rendering graphics.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] Buck had first become interested in GPUs during his undergraduate studies at Princeton University, initially through video gaming.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] After graduation, he interned at Nvidia, gaining deeper exposure to GPU architecture.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] At Stanford, he built an 8K gaming rig using 32 GeForce graphics cards, originally to push the limits of graphics performance in games like Quake and Doom.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] However, his interests shifted toward exploring the potential of GPUs for general-purpose parallel computing.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] To that end, Buck developed Brook, a programming language designed to enable general-purpose computing on GPUs.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] His work attracted support from both Nvidia and the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA).
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] In 2004, Nvidia hired Buck and paired him with John Nickolls, the company's director of architecture for GPU computing.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] Together, they began transforming Brook into what would become CUDA.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] CUDA was officially released by Nvidia in 2007.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] Under the leadership of Nvidia CEO Jensen Huang, CUDA became central to the company's strategy of positioning GPUs as versatile hardware for scientific applications.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] By 2015, CUDA's development increasingly focused on accelerating machine learning and artificial neural network workloads.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] The following table offers a non-exact description for the ontology of the CUDA framework.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] The CUDA platform is accessible to software developers through CUDA-accelerated libraries, compiler directives such as OpenACC, and extensions to industry-standard programming languages including C, C++, Fortran and Python.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] C/C++ programmers can use 'CUDA C/C++', compiled to PTX with nvcc (Nvidia's LLVM-based C/C++ compiler) or by clang itself.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] Fortran programmers can use 'CUDA Fortran', compiled with the PGI CUDA Fortran compiler from The Portland Group.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] Python programmers can use the cuPyNumeric library to accelerate applications on Nvidia GPUs.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] In addition to libraries, compiler directives, CUDA C/C++ and CUDA Fortran, the CUDA platform supports other computational interfaces, including the Khronos Group's OpenCL, Microsoft's DirectCompute, OpenGL Compute Shader and C++ AMP.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] Third party wrappers are also available for Python, Perl, Fortran, Java, Ruby, Lua, Common Lisp, Haskell, R, MATLAB, IDL, Julia, and native support in Mathematica.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] In the computer game industry, GPUs are used for graphics rendering, and for game physics calculations (physical effects such as debris, smoke, fire, fluids); examples include PhysX and Bullet.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] CUDA has also been used to accelerate non-graphical applications in computational biology, cryptography and other fields by an order of magnitude or more.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] CUDA provides both a low level API (CUDA **Driver** API, non single-source) and a higher level API (CUDA **Runtime** API, single-source).
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] The initial CUDA SDK was made public on 15 February 2007, for Microsoft Windows and Linux.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] Mac OS X support was later added in version 2.0, which supersedes the beta released February 14, 2008.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] CUDA works with all Nvidia GPUs from the G8x series onwards, including GeForce, Quadro and the Tesla line.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] CUDA is compatible with most standard operating systems.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] Below is an example given in Python that computes the product of two arrays on the GPU.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] The unofficial Python language bindings can be obtained from *PyCUDA*.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] Additional Python bindings to simplify matrix multiplication operations can be found in the program *pycublas*.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] Note on notation: compute capability X.Y is also written as SMXY or sm_XY (e.g.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] 10.3 as SM103 or sm_103) in professional Nvidia software and the code Nvidia has contributed to LLVM.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] Note: CUDA SDK 10.2 is the last official release for macOS, as support will not be available for macOS in newer releases.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] Note: A GPU with a higher compute capacity is able to execute PTX code meant for a GPU of a lower range of compute capacities.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] However, it is possible to compile CUDA code into a form that only works on one family (same "X") of GPUs; if existing code is compiled this way, recompilation will be needed for it to work on a newer GPU.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] Note: Any missing lines or empty entries do reflect some lack of information on that exact item.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] For more information read the Nvidia CUDA C++ Programming Guide.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] CUDA competes with other GPU computing stacks: Intel OneAPI and AMD ROCm.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] Whereas Nvidia's CUDA is closed-source, Intel's OneAPI and AMD's ROCm are open source.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] Originally made by Intel, other hardware adopters include Fujitsu and Huawei.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] The goal is to offer open alternatives to Nvidia's CUDA.
[src:tensorrt-llm/cuda] The main companies behind it are Intel, Google, ARM, Qualcomm, Samsung, Imagination, and VMware.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Essentially, a GPGPU pipeline is a kind of parallel processing between one or more GPUs and CPUs, with special accelerated instructions for processing image or other graphic forms of data.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] While GPUs operate at lower frequencies, they typically have many times the number of processing elements.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Thus, GPUs can process far more pictures and other graphical data per second than a traditional CPU.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Migrating data into parallel form and then using the GPU to process it can (theoretically) create a large speedup.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPGPU pipelines were developed at the beginning of the 21st century for graphics processing (e.g. for better shaders).
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] From the history of supercomputing it is well-known that scientific computing drives the largest concentrations of Computing power in history, listed in the TOP500: the majority today utilize GPUs.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The best-known GPGPUs are Nvidia Tesla that are used for Nvidia DGX, alongside AMD Instinct and Intel Gaudi.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In principle, any arbitrary Boolean function, including addition, multiplication, and other mathematical functions, can be built up from a functionally complete set of logic operators.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In 1987, Conway's Game of Life became one of the first examples of general-purpose computing using an early stream processor called a blitter to invoke a special sequence of logical operations on bit vectors.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] General-purpose computing on GPUs became more practical and popular after about 2001, with the advent of both programmable shaders and floating point support on graphics processors.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Notably, problems involving matrices and/or vectors – especially two-, three-, or four-dimensional vectors – were easy to translate to a GPU, which acts with native speed and support on those types.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A significant milestone for GPGPU was the year 2003 when two research groups independently discovered GPU-based approaches for the solution of general linear algebra problems on GPUs that ran faster than on CPUs.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] These early efforts to use GPUs as general-purpose processors required reformulating computational problems in terms of graphics primitives, as supported by the two major APIs for graphics processors, OpenGL and Direct3D.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This cumbersome translation was obviated by the advent of general-purpose programming languages and APIs such as Sh/RapidMind, Brook and Accelerator.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] These were followed by Nvidia's CUDA, which allowed programmers to ignore the underlying graphical concepts in favor of more common high-performance computing concepts.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Newer, hardware-vendor-independent offerings include Microsoft's DirectCompute and Apple/Khronos Group's OpenCL.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This means that modern GPGPU pipelines can leverage the speed of a GPU without requiring full and explicit conversion of the data to a graphical form.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Mark Harris, the founder of GPGPU.org, claims he coined the term *GPGPU*.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Any language that allows the code running on the CPU to poll a GPU shader for return values, can create a GPGPU framework.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Programming standards for parallel computing include OpenCL (vendor-independent), OpenACC, OpenMP and OpenHMPP.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] As of 2016, OpenCL is the dominant open general-purpose GPU computing language, and is an open standard defined by the Khronos Group.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] OpenCL provides a cross-platform GPGPU platform that additionally supports data parallel compute on CPUs.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] OpenCL is actively supported on Intel, AMD, Nvidia, and ARM platforms.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The Khronos Group has also standardised and implemented SYCL, a higher-level programming model for OpenCL as a single-source domain specific embedded language based on pure C++11.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The dominant proprietary framework is Nvidia CUDA.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Nvidia launched CUDA in 2006, a software development kit (SDK) and application programming interface (API) that allows using the programming language C to code algorithms for execution on GeForce 8 series and later GPUs.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] ROCm, launched in 2016, is AMD's open-source response to CUDA.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is, as of 2022, on par with CUDA with regards to features, and still lacking in consumer support.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] OpenVIDIA was developed at University of Toronto between 2003–2005, in collaboration with Nvidia.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Altimesh Hybridizer created by Altimesh compiles Common Intermediate Language to CUDA binaries.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It supports generics and virtual functions.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Debugging and profiling is integrated with Visual Studio and Nsight.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is available as a Visual Studio extension on Visual Studio Marketplace.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Microsoft introduced the DirectCompute GPU computing API, released with the Direct3D 11 API.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] MATLAB supports GPGPU acceleration using the *Parallel Computing Toolbox* and *MATLAB Distributed Computing Server*, and third-party packages like Jacket.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPGPU processing is also used to simulate Newtonian physics by physics engines, and commercial implementations include Havok Physics, FX and PhysX, both of which are typically used for computer and video games.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] C++ Accelerated Massive Parallelism (C++ AMP) is a library that accelerates execution of C++ code by exploiting the data-parallel hardware on GPUs.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Due to a trend of increasing power of mobile GPUs, general-purpose programming became available also on the mobile devices running major mobile operating systems.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Google Android 4.2 enabled running RenderScript code on the mobile device GPU.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] RenderScript has since been deprecated in favour of first OpenGL compute shaders and later Vulkan Compute.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] OpenCL is available on many Android devices, but is not officially supported by Android.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Apple introduced the proprietary Metal API for iOS applications, able to execute arbitrary code through Apple's GPU compute shaders.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Originally, data was simply passed one-way from a central processing unit (CPU) to a graphics processing unit (GPU), then to a display device.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] As time progressed, however, it became valuable for GPUs to store at first simple, then complex structures of data to be passed back to the CPU that analyzed an image, or a set of scientific-data represented as a 2D or 3D format that a video card can understand.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Transferring the portion of the data set to be actively analyzed to that GPU memory in the form of textures or other easily readable GPU forms results in speed increase.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The distinguishing feature of a GPGPU design is the ability to transfer information bidirectionally back from the GPU to the CPU; generally the data throughput in both directions is ideally high, resulting in a multiplier effect on the speed of a specific high-use algorithm.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPGPU pipelines may improve efficiency on especially large data sets and/or data containing 2D or 3D imagery.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is used in complex graphics pipelines as well as scientific computing; more so in fields with large data sets like genome mapping, or where two- or three-dimensional analysis is useful – especially at present biomolecule analysis, protein study, and other complex organic chemistry.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] An example of such applications is NVIDIA software suite for genome analysis.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Such pipelines can also vastly improve efficiency in image processing and computer vision, among other fields; as well as parallel processing generally.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Some very heavily optimized pipelines have yielded speed increases of several hundred times the original CPU-based pipeline on one high-use task.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A simple example would be a GPU program that collects data about average lighting values as it renders some view from either a camera or a computer graphics program back to the main program on the CPU, so that the CPU can then make adjustments to the overall screen view.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A more advanced example might use edge detection to return both numerical information and a processed image representing outlines to a computer vision program controlling, say, a mobile robot.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPGPU as a software concept is a type of algorithm, not a piece of equipment.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Specialized equipment designs may, however, even further enhance the efficiency of GPGPU pipelines, which traditionally perform relatively few algorithms on very large amounts of data.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Massively parallelized, gigantic-data-level tasks thus may be parallelized even further via specialized setups such as rack computing (many similar, highly tailored machines built into a *rack*), which adds a third layer – many computing units each using many CPUs to correspond to many GPUs.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Some Bitcoin "miners" used such setups for high-quantity processing.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Insights into the largest such systems in the world has been maintained at the TOP500 supercomputer list.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Historically, CPUs have used hardware-managed caches, but the earlier GPUs only provided software-managed local memories.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] However, as GPUs are being increasingly used for general-purpose applications, state-of-the-art GPUs are being designed with hardware-managed multi-level caches which have helped the GPUs to move towards mainstream computing.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] For example, GeForce 200 series GT200 architecture GPUs did not feature an L2 cache, the Fermi GPU has 768 KiB last-level cache, the Kepler GPU has 1.5 MiB last-level cache, the Maxwell GPU has 2 MiB last-level cache, and the Pascal GPU has 4 MiB last-level cache.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPUs have very large register files, which allow them to reduce context-switching latency.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Register file size is also increasing over different GPU generations, e.g., the total register file size on Maxwell (GM200), Pascal and Volta GPUs are 6 MiB, 14 MiB and 20 MiB, respectively.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] By comparison, the size of a register file on CPUs is small, typically tens or hundreds of kilobytes.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In essence: almost all GPU workloads are inherently massively-parallel LOAD-COMPUTE-STORE in nature, such as tiled rendering.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Even storing one temporary vector for further recall (LOAD-COMPUTE-STORE-COMPUTE-LOAD-COMPUTE-STORE) is so expensive due to the memory wall problem that it is to be avoided at all costs.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The result is that register file size *has* to increase.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In standard CPUs it is possible to introduce caches (a D-cache) to solve this problem, however these are relativrly so large that they are impractical to introduce in GPUs which would need one per processing element.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] ILLIAC IV innovatively solved the problem around 1967 by introducing a local memory per processing element (a PEM): a strategy copied by the Aspex ASP.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Much like how CPUs may elect to implement wider vector instructions in smaller pieces (e.g.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] AMD Bulldozer supported the 256-bit AVX instructions by splitting them into two 128-bit operations) to save power and/or chip area, GPU designers also vary the amount of execution units to fit their expected workloads.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] On a GPGPU, each of the following resources can vary freely in ratio from the others: FP64 (FMA), FP32 (FMA), FP16 (FMA), Int32 Add, Int32 Mul, RCP/RSQRT.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] (An example can be seen in Nvidia's documentation about the execution resources found in each SM of different generation (compute capacity) of GPUs.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is therefore insufficient to simply qualify a GPU's computational capabilities in terms of FLOPS: FLOPS values should be separately presented for matrix vs non-matrix modes and (T)OPS figures should also be presented for integer operations.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The high performance of GPUs comes at the cost of high power consumption, which under full load is in fact as much power as the rest of the PC system combined.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The maximum power consumption of the Pascal series GPU (Tesla P100) was specified to be 250W.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In terms of raw computing power (FLOPS, TOPS, etc.), GPUs tend to have more performance-per-watt than a typical CPU.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] However, it takes a well-written program and a fitting workload to extract most of this power, as most of the time (and power) would otherwise be wasted on local and host memory access.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Before CUDA was published in 2007, GPGPU was "classical" and involved repurposing graphics primitives.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] More examples are available in part 4 of *GPU Gems 2*.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Using GPU for numerical linear algebra began at least in 2001.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It had been used for Gauss-Seidel solver, conjugate gradients, etc.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Computer video cards are produced by various vendors, such as Nvidia, AMD.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Cards from such vendors differ on implementing data-format support, such as integer and floating-point formats (32-bit and 64-bit).
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Microsoft introduced a *Shader Model* standard, to help rank the various features of graphic cards into a simple Shader Model version number (1.0, 2.0, 3.0, etc.).
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Pre-Direct3D 9 video cards only supported paletted or integer color types.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Sometimes another alpha value is added, to be used for transparency.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] For early fixed-function or limited programmability graphics (i.e., up to and including Direct3D 8.1-compliant GPUs) this was sufficient because this is also the representation used in displays.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This representation does have certain limitations.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Given sufficient graphics processing power even graphics programmers would like to use better formats, such as floating point data formats, to obtain effects such as high-dynamic-range imaging.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Many GPGPU applications require floating point accuracy, which came with video cards conforming to the Direct3D 9 specification.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Direct3D 9 Shader Model 2.x suggested the support of two precision types: full and partial precision.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Full precision support could either be FP32 or FP24 (floating point 32- or 24-bit per component) or greater, while partial precision was FP16.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] ATI's Radeon R300 series of GPUs supported FP24 precision only in the programmable fragment pipeline (although FP32 was supported in the vertex processors) while Nvidia's NV30 series supported both FP16 and FP32; other vendors such as S3 Graphics and XGI supported a mixture of formats up to FP24.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The implementations of floating point on Nvidia GPUs are mostly IEEE compliant; however, this is not true across all vendors.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This has implications for correctness which are considered important to some scientific applications.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] While 64-bit floating point values (double precision float) are commonly available on CPUs, these are not universally supported on GPUs.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Some GPU architectures sacrifice IEEE compliance, while others lack double-precision.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Efforts have occurred to emulate double-precision floating point values on GPUs; however, the speed tradeoff negates any benefit to offloading the computing onto the GPU in the first place.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Most operations on the GPU operate in a vectorized fashion: one operation can be performed on up to four values at once.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] For example, if one color ⟨R1, G1, B1⟩ is to be modulated by another color ⟨R2, G2, B2⟩, the GPU can produce the resulting color ⟨R1*R2, G1*G2, B1*B2⟩ in one operation.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This functionality is useful in graphics because almost every basic data type is a vector (either 2-, 3-, or 4-dimensional).
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Examples include vertices, colors, normal vectors, and texture coordinates.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPUs are originally designed specifically for graphics and thus are very restrictive in operations and programming.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Due to their design, GPUs are only effective for problems that can be solved using stream processing and the hardware can only be used in certain ways.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In the early GPGPU age, GPUs can only process independent vertices and fragments, but can process many of them in parallel.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This is especially effective when the programmer wants to process many vertices or fragments in the same way.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In this sense, GPUs are stream processors – processors that can operate in parallel by running one kernel on many records in a stream at once.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Programmers would use graphics APIs (OpenGL or Direct3D) to perform general-purpose computation.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] With the introduction of the CUDA (Nvidia, 2007) and OpenCL (vendor-independent, 2008) general-purpose computing APIs, in new GPGPU codes it is no longer necessary to map the computation to graphics primitives.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The stream processing nature of GPUs remains valid regardless of the APIs used.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A *stream* is simply a set of records that require similar computation.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] *Kernels* are the functions that are applied to each element in the stream.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In the GPUs, *vertices* and *fragments* are the elements in streams and vertex and fragment shaders are the kernels to be run on them.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] For each element we can only read from the input, perform operations on it, and write to the output.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is permissible to have multiple inputs and multiple outputs, but never a piece of memory that is both readable and writable.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Arithmetic intensity is defined as the number of operations performed per word of memory transferred.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is important for GPGPU applications to have high arithmetic intensity else the memory access latency will limit computational speedup.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Ideal GPGPU applications have large data sets, high parallelism, and minimal dependency between data elements.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In fact, a program can substitute a write only texture for output instead of the framebuffer.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This is done either through render-to-texture (RTT), render-to-backbuffer-copy-to-texture (RTBCTT), or the more recent stream-out.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The most common form for a stream to take in GPGPU is a 2D grid because this fits naturally with the rendering model built into GPUs.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Many computations naturally map into grids: matrix algebra, image processing, physically based simulation, and so on.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Since textures are used as memory, texture lookups are then used as memory reads.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Certain operations can be done automatically by the GPU because of this.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Compute kernels can be thought of as the body of loops.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] On the GPU, the programmer only specifies the body of the loop as the kernel and what data to loop over by invoking geometry processing.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] For accurate technical information on this topic see Predication_(computer_architecture)#SIMD,_SIMT_and_vector_predication and ILLIAC IV "branching" (the term "predicate mask" did not exist in 1967).
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In sequential code it is possible to control the flow of the program using if-then-else statements and various forms of loops.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Such flow control structures have only recently been added to GPUs.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Conditional writes could be performed using a properly crafted series of arithmetic/bit operations, but looping and conditional branching were not possible.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Recent GPUs allow branching, but usually with a performance penalty.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Branching should generally be avoided in inner loops, whether in CPU or GPU code, and various methods, such as static branch resolution, pre-computation, predication, loop splitting, and Z-cull can be used to achieve branching when hardware support does not exist.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The map operation simply applies the given function (the kernel) to every element in the stream.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A simple example is multiplying each value in the stream by a constant (increasing the brightness of an image).
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The map operation is simple to implement on the GPU.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The programmer generates a fragment for each pixel on screen and applies a fragment program to each one.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The result stream of the same size is stored in the output buffer.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Some computations require calculating a smaller stream (possibly a stream of only one element) from a larger stream.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This is called a reduction of the stream.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Generally, a reduction can be performed in multiple steps.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The results from the prior step are used as the input for the current step and the range over which the operation is applied is reduced until only one stream element remains.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Stream filtering is essentially a non-uniform reduction.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Filtering involves removing items from the stream based on some criteria.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The scan operation, also termed *parallel prefix sum*, takes in a vector (stream) of data elements and an (arbitrary) associative binary function '+' with an identity element 'i'.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] If the input is [a0, a1, a2, a3, ...], an *exclusive scan* produces the output [i, a0, a0 + a1, a0 + a1 + a2, ...], while an *inclusive scan* produces the output [a0, a0 + a1, a0 + a1 + a2, a0 + a1 + a2 + a3, ...] and does not require an identity to exist.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] While at first glance the operation may seem inherently serial, efficient parallel scan algorithms are possible and have been implemented on graphics processing units.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The scan operation has uses in e.g., quicksort and sparse matrix-vector multiplication.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The scatter operation is most naturally defined on the vertex processor.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The vertex processor is able to adjust the position of the vertex, which allows the programmer to control where information is deposited on the grid.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Other extensions are also possible, such as controlling how large an area the vertex affects.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The fragment processor cannot perform a direct scatter operation because the location of each fragment on the grid is fixed at the time of the fragment's creation and cannot be altered by the programmer.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] However, a logical scatter operation may sometimes be recast or implemented with another gather step.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A scatter implementation would first emit both an output value and an output address.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] An immediately following gather operation uses address comparisons to see whether the output value maps to the current output slot.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In dedicated compute kernels, scatter can be performed by indexed writes.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] After scatter reorders elements according to a map, gather can restore the order of the elements according to the map scatter used.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In dedicated compute kernels, gather may be performed by indexed reads.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In other shaders, it is performed with texture-lookups.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The sort operation transforms an unordered set of elements into an ordered set of elements.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The most common implementation on GPUs is using radix sort for integer and floating point data and coarse-grained merge sort and fine-grained sorting networks for general comparable data.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The search operation allows the programmer to find a given element within the stream, or possibly find neighbors of a specified element.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Mostly the search method used is binary search on sorted elements.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Nvidia recommended GPUs for this application.
[src:tensorrt-llm/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Check with developer or ISV to obtain certification information.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] Almost all modern uses follow the IEEE 754-2008 standard, where the 16-bit base-2 format is referred to as **binary16**, and the exponent uses 5 bits.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] This can express values in the range ±65,504, with the minimum value above 1 being 1 + 1/1024.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] Several earlier 16-bit floating point formats have existed including that of Hitachi's HD61810 DSP of 1982 (a 4-bit exponent and a 12-bit mantissa), the top 16 bits of a 32-bit float (8 exponent and 7 mantissa bits) called a bfloat16, and Thomas J.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] Scott's WIF of 1991 (5 exponent bits, 10 mantissa bits) and the 3dfx Voodoo Graphics processor of 1995 (same as Hitachi).
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] ILM was searching for an image format that could handle a wide dynamic range, but without the hard drive and memory cost of single or double precision floating point.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] The hardware-accelerated programmable shading group led by John Airey at SGI (Silicon Graphics) used the s10e5 data type in 1997 as part of the "bali" design effort.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] This is described in a SIGGRAPH 2000 paper (see section 4.3) and further documented in US patent 7518615.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] It was popularized by its use in the open-source OpenEXR image format.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] Nvidia and Microsoft defined the **half** datatype in the Cg language, released in early 2002, and implemented it in silicon in the GeForce FX, released in late 2002.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] However, hardware support for accelerated 16-bit floating point was later dropped by Nvidia before being reintroduced in the Tegra X1 mobile GPU in 2015.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] The F16C extension in 2012 allows x86 processors to convert half-precision floats to and from single-precision floats with a machine instruction.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] The format is assumed to have an implicit lead bit with value 1 unless the exponent field is stored with all zeros.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] Thus, only 10 bits of the significand appear in the memory format but the total precision is 11 bits.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] In IEEE 754 parlance, there are 10 bits of significand, but there are 11 bits of significand precision (log10(211) ≈ 3.311 decimal digits, or 4 digits ± slightly less than 5 units in the last place).
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] The half-precision binary floating-point exponent is encoded using an offset-binary representation, with the zero offset being 15; also known as exponent bias in the IEEE 754 standard.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] Thus, as defined by the offset binary representation, in order to get the true exponent the offset of 15 has to be subtracted from the stored exponent.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] The stored exponents 000002 and 111112 are interpreted specially.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] The minimum strictly positive (subnormal) value is 2−24 ≈ 5.96 × 10−8.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] The minimum positive normal value is 2−14 ≈ 6.10 × 10−5.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] These examples are given in bit representation of the floating-point value.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] This includes the sign bit, (biased) exponent, and significand.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] By default, 1/3 rounds down like for double precision, because of the odd number of bits in the significand.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] The bits beyond the rounding point are 0101... which is less than 1/2 of a unit in the last place.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] ARM processors support (via a floating-point control register bit) an "alternative half-precision" format, which does away with the special case for an exponent value of 31 (111112).
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] It is almost identical to the IEEE format, but there is no encoding for infinity or NaNs; instead, an exponent of 31 encodes normalized numbers in the range 65536 to 131008.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] Half precision is used in several computer graphics environments to store pixels, including MATLAB, OpenEXR, JPEG XR, GIMP, OpenGL, Vulkan, Cg, Direct3D, and D3DX.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] The advantage over 8-bit or 16-bit integers is that the increased dynamic range allows for more detail to be preserved in highlights and shadows for images, and avoids gamma correction.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] The advantage over 32-bit single-precision floating point is that it requires half the storage and bandwidth (at the expense of precision and range).
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] Half precision can be useful for mesh quantization.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] Mesh data is usually stored using 32-bit single-precision floats for the vertices, however in some situations it is acceptable to reduce the precision to only 16-bit half-precision, requiring only half the storage at the expense of some precision.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] Mesh quantization can also be done with 8-bit or 16-bit fixed precision depending on the requirements.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] Hardware and software for machine learning and neural networks often use half-precision arithmetic to accelerate computations.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] In these applications, the distinct bfloat16 format is sometimes preferred for its wider dynamic range than half-precision, and specialized floating point formats with only 8 bits or less are increasingly used to further accelerate certain computations.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] If the hardware has instructions to compute half-precision math, it is often faster than single or double precision, sometimes up to 4 times faster.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] In addition if the system has SIMD instructions, often one instruction can simultaneously operate on twice as many half values than float values.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] Zig, Odin, and other languages provide support for half precisions with their `f16` type.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] .NET 5 introduced half precision floating point numbers with the `System.Half` standard library type.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] As of 16 July 2025, no .NET language (C#, F#, Visual Basic, and C++/CLI and C++/CX) has literals (e.g. in C#, `1.0f` has type `System.Single` or `1.0m` has type `System.Decimal`) or a keyword for the type.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] Swift introduced half-precision floating point numbers in Swift 5.3 with the `Float16` type.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] OpenCL also supports half-precision floating point numbers with the half datatype on IEEE 754-2008 half-precision storage format.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] As of 31 May 2026, Rust is currently working on adding a new `f16` type for IEEE half-precision 16-bit floats.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] Julia provides support for half-precision floating point numbers with the `Float16` type.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] C++ introduced half-precision since C++23 with the `std::float16_t` type.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] Several versions of the ARM architecture have support for half precision.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] Support for conversions with half-precision floats in the x86 instruction set is specified in the F16C instruction set extension, first introduced in 2009 by AMD and fairly broadly adopted by AMD and Intel CPUs by 2012.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] This was further extended up the AVX-512_FP16 instruction set extension implemented in the Intel Sapphire Rapids processor.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] On RISC-V, the `Zfh` and `Zfhmin` extensions provide hardware support for 16-bit half precision floats.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] The `Zfhmin` extension is a minimal alternative to `Zfh`.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] On Power ISA, VSX and the not-yet-approved SVP64 extension provide hardware support for 16-bit half-precision floats as of PowerISA v3.1B and later.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] Support for half precision on IBM Z is part of the Neural-network-processing-assist facility that IBM introduced with Telum.
[src:tensorrt-llm/half-precision-floating-point-format] IBM refers to half precision floating point data as NNP-Data-Type 1 (16-bit).
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Originally focused on GPUs for video games, Nvidia broadened their use into other markets, including artificial intelligence (AI), professional visualization, and supercomputing.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] The company's product lines include GeForce GPUs for gaming and creative workloads, and professional GPUs for edge computing, scientific research, and industrial applications.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] As of the first quarter of 2025, Nvidia held a 92% share of the discrete desktop and laptop GPU market.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In the early-to-mid 2000s, the company invested over a billion dollars to develop CUDA, a software platform and API (Application Programming Interfaces) that enabled GPUs to run massively parallel programs for a broad range of compute-intensive applications.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] As a result, as of 2025, Nvidia controlled more than 80% of the market for GPUs used in training and deploying AI models, and provided chips for over 75% of the world's TOP500 supercomputers.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] The company has also expanded into gaming hardware and services, with products such as the Shield Portable, Shield Tablet, and Shield TV, and operates the GeForce Now cloud gaming service.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Furthermore, it has developed the Tegra line of mobile processors for smartphones, tablets, and automotive infotainment systems.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In 2023, Nvidia became the seventh U.S. company to reach a US$1 trillion valuation.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In 2025, amid increased demand for AI data center hardware in the midst of the AI boom, Nvidia became the first company in the world to surpass US$4 trillion and US$5 trillion in market capitalization.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Because of its market capitalization and role in major technology indexes, Nvidia has been selected as one of Bloomberg's "Magnificent Seven", the seven biggest companies on the stock market in these regards.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In late 1992, the three men agreed to start the company in a meeting at a Denny's roadside diner on Berryessa Road in East San Jose.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] At the time, Malachowsky and Priem were frustrated with Sun's management and were looking to leave, but Huang was on "firmer ground", in that he was already running his own division at LSI.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] The three co-founders discussed a vision of the future which was so compelling that Huang decided to leave LSI and become the chief executive officer of their new startup.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] The three co-founders envisioned graphics-based processing as the best trajectory for tackling challenges that had eluded general-purpose computing methods.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] As Huang later explained: "We also observed that video games were simultaneously one of the most computationally challenging problems and would have incredibly high sales volume.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Those two conditions don't happen very often.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] The first problem was who would quit first.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Huang's wife, Lori, did not want him to resign from LSI unless Malachowsky resigned from Sun at the same time, and Malachowsky's wife, Melody, felt the same way about Huang.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Priem broke that deadlock by resigning first from Sun, effective December 31, 1992.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] According to Priem, this put pressure on Huang and Malachowsky to not leave him to "flail alone", so they gave notice too.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Huang left LSI and "officially joined Priem on February 17", which was also Huang's 30th birthday, while Malachowsky left Sun in early March.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In early 1993, the three founders began working together on their new startup in Priem's townhouse in Fremont, California.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] With $40,000 in the bank (equivalent to $89,000 in 2025), the company was born.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] The company subsequently received $20 million of venture capital funding from Sequoia Capital, Sutter Hill Ventures, and others.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] During the late 1990s, Nvidia was one of 70 startup companies pursuing the idea that graphics acceleration for video games was the path to the future.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Only two survived: Nvidia and ATI Technologies, the latter of which merged into AMD.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Priem's first idea was "Primal Graphics", a syllabic abbreviation of two of the founders' last names, but that left out Huang.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] They soon discovered it was impossible to create a workable name with syllables from all three founders' names, after considering "Huaprimal", "Prihuamal", "Malluapri", etc.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] The next idea came from Priem's idea for the name of Nvidia's first product.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Priem originally wanted to call it the "GXNV", as in the "next version" of the GX graphics chips which he had worked on at Sun.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Then Huang told Priem to "drop the GX", resulting in the name "NV".
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Priem made a list of words with the letters "NV" in them.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] At one point, Malachowsky and Priem wanted to call the company NVision, but that name was already taken by a manufacturer of toilet paper.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Both Priem and Huang have taken credit for coming up with the name Nvidia, from "invidia", the Latin word for "envy".
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] After the company outgrew Priem's townhouse, its original headquarters office was in Sunnyvale, California.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Nvidia's first graphics accelerator, the NV1, was designed to process quadrilateral primitives (forward texture mapping), a feature that set it apart from competitors, who preferred triangle primitives.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] However, when Microsoft introduced the DirectX platform, it chose not to support any other graphics software and announced that its Direct3D API would exclusively support triangles.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] As a result, the NV1 failed to gain traction in the market.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Nvidia had also entered into a partnership with Sega to supply the graphics chip for the Dreamcast console and worked on the project for about a year.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] However, Nvidia's technology was already lagging behind competitors.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] This placed the company in a difficult position: continue working on a chip that was likely doomed to fail or abandon the project, risking financial collapse.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In a pivotal moment, Sega's president, Shoichiro Irimajiri, visited Huang in person to inform him that Sega had decided to choose another vendor for the Dreamcast.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] However, Irimajiri believed in Nvidia's potential and persuaded Sega's management to invest $5 million into the company.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Huang later reflected that this funding was all that kept Nvidia afloat, and that Irimajiri's "understanding and generosity gave us six months to live".
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In 1996, Huang laid off more than half of Nvidia's employees-reducing headcount from 100 to 40-and focused the company's remaining resources on developing a graphics accelerator product optimized for processing triangle primitives: the RIVA 128.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] By the time the RIVA 128 was released in August 1997, Nvidia had only enough money left for one month's payroll.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] The sense of impending failure became so pervasive that it gave rise to Nvidia's unofficial company motto: "Our company is thirty days from going out of business." Huang began internal presentations to Nvidia staff with those words for many years.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Nvidia sold about a million RIVA 128 units within four months, and used the revenue to fund development of its next generation of products.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In 1998, the release of the RIVA TNT helped solidify Nvidia's reputation as a leader in graphics technology.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Investing in Nvidia after it had already failed to deliver on its contract turned out to be Irimajiri's best decision as Sega's president.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] After Irimajiri left Sega in 2000, Sega sold its Nvidia stock for $15 million.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In late 1999, Nvidia released the GeForce 256 (NV10), its first product expressly marketed as a GPU, which was most notable for introducing onboard transformation and lighting (T&L) to consumer-level 3D hardware.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Running at 120 MHz and featuring four-pixel pipelines, it implemented advanced video acceleration, motion compensation, and hardware sub-picture alpha blending.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] The GeForce outperformed existing products by a wide margin.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Because its products were performing well, Nvidia won the contract to develop the graphics hardware for Microsoft's Xbox game console, which included a $200 million advance.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] However, the project took many of its best engineers away from other projects.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In the short term this did not matter, and the GeForce 2 GTS shipped in the summer of 2000.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In December 2000, Nvidia reached an agreement to acquire the intellectual assets of its one-time rival 3dfx, a pioneer in consumer 3D graphics technology leading the field from the mid-1990s until 2000.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] The acquisition process was finalized in April 2002.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In 2001, Standard & Poor's selected Nvidia to replace the departing Enron in the S&P 500 stock index, meaning that index funds would need to hold Nvidia shares going forward.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In July 2002, Nvidia acquired Exluna for an undisclosed sum.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Exluna made software-rendering tools and its personnel were merged into Nvidia's Cg project.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In August 2003, Nvidia acquired MediaQ for approximately US$70 million.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] On April 22, 2004, Nvidia acquired iReady, also a provider of high-performance TCP offload engines and iSCSI controllers.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In December 2004, it was announced that Nvidia would assist Sony with the design of the graphics processor (RSX) for the PlayStation 3 game console.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] On December 14, 2005, Nvidia acquired ULI Electronics, which at the time supplied third-party southbridge parts for chipsets to ATI, Nvidia's competitor.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In March 2006, Nvidia acquired Hybrid Graphics.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In December 2006, Nvidia, along with its main rival in the graphics industry AMD (which had acquired ATI), received subpoenas from the United States Department of Justice regarding possible antitrust violations in the graphics card industry.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In July 2008, Nvidia took a write-down of approximately $200 million on its first-quarter revenue, after reporting that certain mobile chipsets and GPUs produced by the company had "abnormal failure rates" due to manufacturing defects.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Nvidia, however, did not reveal the affected products.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In September 2008, Nvidia became the subject of a class action lawsuit over the defects, claiming that the faulty GPUs had been incorporated into certain laptop models manufactured by Apple Inc., Dell, and HP.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In September 2010, Nvidia reached a settlement, in which it would reimburse owners of the affected laptops for repairs or, in some cases, replacement.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] On January 10, 2011, Nvidia signed a six-year, $1.5 billion cross-licensing agreement with Intel, ending all litigation between the two companies.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In November 2011, after initially unveiling it at Mobile World Congress, Nvidia released its ARM-based system on a chip for mobile devices, Tegra 3.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Nvidia claimed that the chip featured the first-ever quad-core mobile CPU.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In May 2011, it was announced that Nvidia had agreed to acquire Icera, a baseband chip making company in the UK, for $367 million.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In January 2013, Nvidia unveiled the Tegra 4, as well as the Nvidia Shield, an Android-based handheld game console powered by the new system on a chip.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] On July 29, 2013, Nvidia announced that it acquired PGI from STMicroelectronics.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In February 2013, Nvidia announced its plans to build a new headquarters in the form of two giant triangle-shaped buildings on the other side of San Tomas Expressway (to the west of its existing headquarters complex).
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] The company selected triangles as its design theme.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] As Huang explained in a blog post, the triangle is "the fundamental building block of computer graphics".
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In 2014, Nvidia ported the Valve games *Portal* and *Half Life 2* to its Nvidia Shield Tablet as Lightspeed Studio.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Since 2014, Nvidia has diversified its business focusing on three markets: gaming, automotive electronics, and mobile devices.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] That same year, Nvidia also prevailed in litigation brought by the trustee of 3dfx's bankruptcy estate to challenge its 2000 acquisition of 3dfx's intellectual assets.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] On May 6, 2016, Nvidia unveiled the first GPUs of the GeForce 10 series, the GTX 1080 and 1070, based on the company's new Pascal microarchitecture.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Nvidia claimed that both models outperformed its Maxwell-based Titan X model; the models incorporate GDDR5X and GDDR5 memory respectively, and use a 16 nm manufacturing process.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] The architecture also supports a new hardware feature known as simultaneous multi-projection (SMP), which is designed to improve the quality of multi-monitor and virtual reality (VR) rendering.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Laptops that include these GPUs and are sufficiently thin – as of late 2017, under 0.8 inches (20 mm) – have been designated as meeting Nvidia's "Max-Q" design standard.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In July 2016, Nvidia agreed to a settlement for a false advertising lawsuit regarding its GTX 970 model, as the models were unable to use all of their advertised 4 GB of VRAM due to limitations brought by the design of its hardware.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In May 2017, Nvidia announced a partnership with Toyota which would use Nvidia's Drive PX-series artificial intelligence platform for its autonomous vehicles.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In July 2017, Nvidia and Chinese search giant Baidu announced a far-reaching AI partnership that includes cloud computing, autonomous driving, consumer devices, and Baidu's open-source AI framework PaddlePaddle.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Baidu unveiled that Nvidia's Drive PX 2 AI will be the foundation of its autonomous-vehicle platform.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Nvidia released the Titan V on December 7, 2017.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Nvidia released the Nvidia Quadro GV100 on March 27, 2018.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Nvidia released the RTX 2080 GPUs on September 27, 2018.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In 2018, Google announced that Nvidia's Tesla P4 graphic cards would be integrated into Google Cloud service's artificial intelligence.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In May 2018, on the Nvidia user forum, a thread was started asking the company to update users when it would release web drivers for its cards installed on legacy Mac Pro machines up to mid-2012 5,1 running the macOS Mojave operating system 10.14.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Web drivers are required to enable graphics acceleration and multiple display monitor capabilities of the GPU.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] On its Mojave update info website, Apple stated that macOS Mojave would run on legacy machines with 'Metal compatible' graphics cards and listed Metal compatible GPUs, including some manufactured by Nvidia.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] However, this list did not include Metal compatible cards that currently work in macOS High Sierra using Nvidia-developed web drivers.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In September, Nvidia responded, "Apple fully controls drivers for macOS.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] But if Apple allows, our engineers are ready and eager to help Apple deliver great drivers for macOS 10.14 (Mojave)." In October, Nvidia followed this up with another public announcement, "Apple fully controls drivers for macOS.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Unfortunately, Nvidia currently cannot release a driver unless it is approved by Apple," suggesting a possible rift between the two companies.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] By January 2019, with still no sign of the enabling web drivers, Apple Insider weighed into the controversy with a claim that Apple management "doesn't want Nvidia support in macOS".
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] The following month, Apple Insider followed this up with another claim that Nvidia support was abandoned because of "relational issues in the past", and that Apple was developing its own GPU technology.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Without Apple-approved Nvidia web drivers, Apple users are faced with replacing their Nvidia cards with a competing supported brand, such as AMD Radeon from the list recommended by Apple.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] On March 11, 2019, Nvidia announced a deal to buy Mellanox Technologies for $6.9 billion to substantially expand its footprint in the high-performance computing market.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] The acquisition of the Israeli firm, a longtime supplier to the Israeli military, led to the 2023 launch of "Israel-1," described as the country's most powerful AI supercomputer.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In May 2019, Nvidia announced new RTX Studio laptops.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] The creators said that the new laptop was going to be seven times faster than a top-end MacBook Pro with a Core i9 and AMD's Radeon Pro Vega 20 graphics in apps like Maya and RedCine-X Pro.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In August 2019, Nvidia announced *Minecraft RTX*, an official Nvidia-developed patch for the game *Minecraft* adding real-time DXR ray tracing exclusively to the Windows 10 version of the game.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] The whole game was, in Nvidia's words, "refit" with path tracing, which dramatically affects the way light, reflections, and shadows work inside the engine.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In May 2020, Nvidia announced it was acquiring Cumulus Networks.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Post acquisition the company was absorbed into Nvidia's networking business unit, along with Mellanox.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In May 2020, Nvidia developed an open-source ventilator to address the shortage resulting from the global coronavirus pandemic.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] On May 14, 2020, Nvidia officially announced its Ampere GPU microarchitecture and the Nvidia A100 GPU accelerator.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In July 2020, it was reported that Nvidia was in talks with SoftBank to buy Arm, a UK-based chip designer, for $32 billion.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] On September 1, 2020, Nvidia officially announced the GeForce 30 series based on the company's new Ampere microarchitecture.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] On September 13, 2020, Nvidia announced that it would buy Arm from SoftBank Group for $40 billion, subject to the usual scrutiny, with the latter retaining a 10% share of Nvidia.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In October 2020, Nvidia announced its plan to build the most powerful computer in Cambridge, England.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] The computer, called Cambridge-1, launched in July 2021 with a $100 million investment and will employ AI to support healthcare research.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Also in October 2020, along with the release of the Nvidia RTX A6000, Nvidia announced it was retiring its workstation GPU brand Quadro, shifting its product name to Nvidia RTX for future products and the manufacturing to be Ampere architecture-based.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In August 2021, the proposed takeover of Arm was stalled after the UK's Competition and Markets Authority raised "significant competition concerns".
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In October 2021, the European Commission opened a competition investigation into the takeover.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] The Commission stated that Nvidia's acquisition could restrict competitors' access to Arm's products and provide Nvidia with too much internal information on its competitors due to their deals with Arm.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] SoftBank (the parent company of Arm) and Nvidia announced in early February 2022 that they "had agreed not to move forward with the transaction 'because of significant regulatory challenges'".
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] The investigation was set to end on March 15, 2022.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] That same month, Nvidia was reportedly compromised by a cyberattack.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] This would have been the largest semiconductor acquisition in history.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In March 2022, Nvidia's CEO Jensen Huang mentioned that they were open to having Intel manufacture their chips in the future.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] This was the first time the company mentioned that it would work together with Intel's upcoming foundry services.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In April 2022, it was reported that Nvidia planned to open a new research center in Yerevan, Armenia.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In May 2022, Nvidia opened Voyager, the second of the two giant buildings at its new headquarters complex to the west of the old one.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Unlike its smaller and older sibling Endeavor, the triangle theming is used more "sparingly" in Voyager.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In September 2022, Nvidia announced its next-generation automotive-grade chip, Drive Thor.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In September 2022, Nvidia announced a collaboration with the Broad Institute of MIT and Harvard related to the entire suite of Nvidia's AI-powered healthcare software suite called Clara, that includes Parabricks and MONAI.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Following United States Department of Commerce regulations which placed an embargo on exports to China of advanced microchips, which went into effect in October 2022, Nvidia saw its data center chip added to the export control list.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] The next month, the company unveiled a new advanced chip in China, called the A800 GPU, that met the export control rules.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In September 2023, Getty Images announced that it was partnering with Nvidia to launch Generative AI by Getty Images, a new tool that let people create images using Getty's library of licensed photos.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Getty said they would use Nvidia's Edify model, which was available on Nvidia's generative AI model library Picasso.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] On September 26, 2023, Denny's CEO Kelli Valade joined Huang in East San Jose to celebrate the founding of Nvidia at Denny's on Berryessa Road, where a plaque was installed to mark the relevant corner booth as the birthplace of a $1 trillion company.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] By then, Nvidia's H100 GPUs were in such demand that even other tech giants were beholden to how Nvidia allocated supply.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Larry Ellison of Oracle Corporation said that month that during a dinner with Huang at Nobu in Palo Alto, he and Elon Musk of Tesla, Inc. and xAI "were begging" for H100s, "I guess is the best way to describe it.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In October 2023, it was reported that Nvidia had quietly begun designing ARM-based central processing units (CPUs) for Microsoft's Windows operating system with a target to start selling them in 2025.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In January 2024, *Forbes* reported that Nvidia has increased its lobbying presence in Washington, D.C. as American lawmakers consider proposals to regulate artificial intelligence.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] From 2023 to 2024, the company reportedly hired at least four government affairs with professional backgrounds at agencies including the United States Department of State and the Department of the Treasury.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] It was noted that the $350,000 spent by the company on lobbying in 2023 was small compared to a number of major tech companies in the artificial intelligence space.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In January 2024, Raymond James Financial analysts estimated that Nvidia was selling the H100 GPU in the price range of $25,000 to $30,000 each, while on eBay, individual H100s cost over $40,000.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Several major technology companies were purchasing tens or hundreds of thousands of GPUs for their data centers to run generative artificial intelligence projects; simple arithmetic implied that they were committing to billions of dollars in capital expenditures.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In February 2024, it was reported that Nvidia was the "hot employer" in Silicon Valley because it was offering interesting work and good pay at a time when other tech employers were downsizing.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Half of Nvidia employees earned over $228,000 in 2023.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] By then, Nvidia GPUs had become so valuable that they needed special security while in transit to data centers.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Cisco chief information officer Fletcher Previn explained at a CIO summit: "Those GPUs arrive by armored car".
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] On March 1, 2024, Nvidia became the third company in the history of the United States to close with a market capitalization in excess of $2 trillion.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Nvidia needed only 180 days to get to $2 trillion from $1 trillion, while the first two companies, Apple and Microsoft, each took over 500 days.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] On March 18, Nvidia announced its new AI chip and microarchitecture Blackwell, named after mathematician David Blackwell.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In April 2024, Reuters reported that China had allegedly acquired banned Nvidia chips and servers from Supermicro and Dell via tenders.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In June 2024, the Federal Trade Commission (FTC) and the Justice Department (DOJ) began antitrust investigations into Nvidia, Microsoft and OpenAI, focusing on their influence in the AI industry.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] The FTC led the investigations into Microsoft and OpenAI, while the DOJ handled Nvidia.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] The probes centered on the companies' conduct rather than mergers.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] This development followed an open letter from OpenAI employees expressing concerns about the rapid AI advancements and lack of oversight.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] The company became the world's most valuable, surpassing Microsoft and Apple, on June 18, 2024, after its market capitalization exceeded $3.3 trillion.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In June 2024, Trend Micro announced a partnership with Nvidia to develop AI-driven security tools, notably to protect the data centers where AI workloads are processed.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] This collaboration integrates Nvidia NIM and Nvidia Morpheus with Trend Vision One and its Sovereign and Private Cloud solutions to improve data privacy, real-time analysis, and rapid threat mitigation.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In October 2024, Nvidia introduced a family of open-source multimodal large language models called NVLM 1.0, which features a flagship version with 72 billion parameters, designed to improve text-only performance after multimodal training.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In October 2024, Nvidia reported that it had been collaborating with Raytheon (a RTX Corporation business) to “explore network pipelines that accelerate workloads on GPUs and use GPU acceleration software libraries”.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In November 2024, the company was added to the Dow Jones Industrial Average.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In November 2024, Morgan Stanley reported that "the entire 2025 production" of all of Nvidia's Blackwell chips was "already sold out".
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Also in November 2024, the company bought 1.2 million shares of Nebius Group.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Nvidia was ranked #3 on Forbes' "Best Places to Work" list in 2024.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] As of January 7, 2025, Nvidia's $3.66 trillion market cap was worth more than double of the combined value of AMD, ARM, Broadcom, and Intel.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In January 2025, Nvidia saw the largest one-day loss in market capitalization for a U.S. company in history at $600 billion.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] This was due to DeepSeek, a Chinese AI startup that developed an advanced AI model at a lower cost and computing power.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] DeepSeek's AI assistant, using the V3 model, surpassed ChatGPT as the highest-rated free app in the U.S. on Apple's App Store.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] On April 7, 2025, Nvidia released the Llama-3.1-Nemotron-Ultra-253B-v1 reasoning large language model, under the Nvidia Open Model License.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] It comes in three sizes: Nano, Super and Ultra.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] On May 28, 2025, Nvidia's second-quarter revenue forecast fell short of market estimates due to U.S. export restrictions impacting AI chip sales to China, yet the company's stock rose 5% as investors remained optimistic about long-term AI demand.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In July 2025, it was announced that Nvidia had acquired CentML, a Canadian-based AI firm.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] On July 10, 2025, Nvidia closed for the first time with a market cap above $4 trillion, after its market cap briefly touched and then retreated from that number during the previous day.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Nvidia became the first company to reach a market cap of $4 trillion.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] At that point, Nvidia was worth more than the combined value of all publicly traded companies in the United Kingdom.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] On July 29, 2025, Nvidia ordered 300,000 H20 AI chips from Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company (TSMC) due to strong demand from Chinese tech firms like Tencent and Alibaba.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In August 2025, Nvidia and competitor Advanced Micro Devices agreed to pay 15% of the revenues from certain chip sales in China as part of an arrangement to obtain export licenses.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Nvidia will pay only for sales of the H20 chips.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] China's internet regulator banned the country's largest technology companies from buying Nvidia's artificial intelligence chips as part of efforts to strengthen the domestic industry and compete with the United States.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] The CAC instructed companies this week to end both testing and orders of the RTX Pro 6000D, which Nvidia had designed as a tailor-made product for China, according to three people with knowledge of the matter.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] On September 18, 2025, Nvidia announced it would invest $5 billion in Intel, backing the struggling U.S. chipmaker just weeks after the White House arranged a deal for the federal government to take a major stake in the company.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] The investment will give Nvidia an immediate holding of about 4% in Intel once new shares are issued to finalize the agreement.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Nvidia's move provides Intel with fresh support following years of unsuccessful turnaround efforts and will allow Nvidia to offer its powerful GB300 data center servers based on Blackwell GPUs on Intel's X86 architecture.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] On September 22, 2025, Nvidia and OpenAI announced a memorandum of understanding for a partnership wherein Nvidia would invest $100 billion into OpenAI, and OpenAI would use Nvidia chips and systems in new data centers.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] OpenAI will build new AI data centers using Nvidia systems, amounting to at least 10 gigawatts system power, which is the equivalent of energy produced by more than four Hoover Dams.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] The deal was meant to be a circular arrangement where OpenAI will pay back Nvidia's investment through the purchase of Nvidia's chips, which is a model common in AI partnerships.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] This "circularity" is estimated at $35 billion in new Nvidia chips bought by OpenAI, for every $10 billion Nvidia invests in OpenAI.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] As of January 2026, negotiations had not progressed beyond early stages, and the two companies were rethinking the partnership's structure.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In the months leading up to this, chief executive Jensen Huang privately emphasized to industry associates that the original deal was non-binding and not finalized when announced.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Dubbed "Aurora", the facility is expected to set a new flexible power standard.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] A server farm dedicated to autonomous AI was also announced in October 2025, as a collaboration between SDS Schönfeld, a data services firm owned by UC Schönfeld, and VAST Data, an Israeli company specializing in AI storage management that collaborates closely with Nvidia.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Reports indicate that approximately $30 billion has been secured for the Bet Yehoshua server farm.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] On October 29, 2025, Nvidia became the first company to reach a market capitalization of $5 trillion.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Nvidia's stock prices fell by 2% on November 11, 2025, as the SoftBank Group dumped its entire Nvidia portfolio worth $5.8 billion, redirecting the capital towards OpenAI instead.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] On December 1, 2025, Nvidia released Alpamayo-R1, an open source, vision-language-action AI model for self-driving vehicles.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] This was done so that developers and researchers can understand how these models work and come up with standard ways on how the industry can evaluate how they work.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] On December 15, 2025, Nvidia announced the Nemotron 3 family of models consisting of Nano, Super and Ultra models, built on a hybrid mixture-of-experts (MoE) architecture.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Nvidia said Nano has around 30 billion parameters, Super 100 billion, and Ultra 500 billion.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] On December 18, 2025, Nvidia announced plans to build a major new research and development campus in Kiryat Tivon, Israel, projected to employ more than 10,000 people and become one of the company's largest sites outside the United States.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] The 22-acre complex is scheduled to begin construction in 2027, with initial operations expected in 2031, and will include laboratories, green areas, and public facilities.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] The project reinforces Israel's role as Nvidia's principal international development hub in advanced AI and computing technologies.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In December 2025, it was announced that Nvidia had acquired SchedMD, the company behind the open-source workload manager Slurm, as part of an effort to expand its AI and high-performance computing software capabilities.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Nvidia stated that Slurm would remain open-source and vendor-neutral after the acquisition, with no financial terms disclosed.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In December 2025, CNBC reported Nvidia had agreed to buy assets from Groq for $20 billion in cash.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] The deal included a non-exclusive licensing agreement with Nvidia for Groq's inference technology.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Several of Groq's senior leaders, including its CEO, also agreed to join Nvidia as part of the deal.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] While both companies said Groq would continue to operate as an individual company, the transaction drew criticism from several industry analysts as a tactic to avoid regulatory scrutiny.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In late 2025, Nvidia entered advanced negotiations to acquire AI21 Labs, an Israeli developer of large language models, in a deal valued at as much as $2 billion to $3 billion.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] The proposed transaction is widely described as a talent-focused "acquihire" aimed at integrating AI21's workforce of approximately 200 specialists into Nvidia's global artificial intelligence operations.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] If completed, the transaction would be Nvidia's second-largest Israeli acquisition after its $7 billion purchase of Mellanox in 2020.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] At CES 2026, CEO Jensen Huang unveiled Nvidia's Vera Rubin AI platform and the Alpamayo open-source model.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Hesai was also picked as Nvidia's laser technology partner, supplying Lidar sensors to the company, streamlining software, hardware, and data in its autonomous driving products.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In January 2026, Nvidia launched a new weather forecasting service called Earth-2.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] It is an open-sourced platform that can be incorporated to improve the AI function across models used by scientists, businesses and local governments.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] On February 24, 2026, Nvidia announced its acquisition of Israeli startup Illumex, a developer of generative semantic data infrastructure, in a deal reportedly valued at around $60 million.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] On March 11, 2026, Nvidia announced that it will invest $2 billion in artificial intelligence cloud company Nebius.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In April 2026, Nvidia announced the release of a new group of open-source artificial intelligence models designed specifically for quantum computing.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] The development caused a noticeable market surge for allied quantum computing companies.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] During the same month, Nvidia's market momentum was further bolstered by its primary manufacturing partner, TSMC, which reported a 35.1% year-on-year revenue increase for the first quarter of 2026, largely driven by robust global demand for AI accelerators.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] At the GTC conference in March 2026, Nvidia announced the "Vera Rubin" platform, the successor to its Blackwell architecture.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] The platform includes the Rubin GPU and Vera CPU, designed to scale "agentic AI" and offering significant performance improvements in large-scale AI factories.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In May 2026, Nvidia announced that it would be partnering with Corning and investing up to 3.2 billion to build 3 new advanced manufacturing facilities in North Carolina and Texas as part of a optical fiber deal.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] On June 1, 2026, Nvidia released the RTX Spark chip intended for laptops.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] For the fiscal year 2020, Nvidia reported earnings of US$2.796 billion, with an annual revenue of US$10.918 billion, a decline of 6.8% over the previous fiscal cycle.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Nvidia's shares traded at over $531 per share, and its market capitalization was valued at over US$328.7 billion in January 2021.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] For the Q2 of 2020, Nvidia reported sales of $3.87 billion, which was a 50% rise from the same period in 2019.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] The surge in sales was driven by people's higher demand for computer technology.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Nvidia uses external suppliers for all phases of manufacturing, including wafer fabrication, assembly, testing, and packaging.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Nvidia thus avoids most of the investment and production costs and risks associated with chip manufacturing, although it does sometimes directly procure some components and materials used in the production of its products (e.g., memory and substrates).
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Nvidia focuses its own resources on product design, quality assurance, marketing, and customer support.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Nvidia's GPU Technology Conference (GTC) is a series of technical conferences held around the world.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] It originated in 2009 in San Jose, California, with an initial focus on the potential for solving computing challenges through GPUs.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In recent years, the conference's focus has shifted to various applications of artificial intelligence and deep learning; including self-driving cars, healthcare, high-performance computing, and Nvidia Deep Learning Institute (DLI) training.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] GTC 2020 was converted to a digital event and drew roughly 59,000 registrants.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] After several years of remote-only events, GTC in March 2024 returned to an in-person format in San Jose, California.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] At GTC 2025, Nvidia unveiled its next-generation AI hardware, the Blackwell Ultra and Vera Rubin chips, signalling a leap toward agentic AI and reasoning-capable computing.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Huang projected that AI-driven infrastructure would drive Nvidia's data center revenue to $1 trillion by 2028.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] The announcement also introduced Isaac GR00T N1 (humanoid robotics model), Cosmos (synthetic training data AI), and the Newton physics engine, developed in collaboration with DeepMind and Disney Research.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Until September 23, 2013, Nvidia had not published any documentation for its advanced hardware, meaning that programmers could not write free and open-source device drivers for its products without resorting to reverse engineering.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Additionally, features like its compute platform CUDA and the DLSS technology suite are proprietary and only available on its hardware.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] As such, Nvidia has been notable for proprietization and vendor-locking practices.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Instead, Nvidia provides its own binary GeForce graphics drivers for X.Org and an open-source library that interfaces with the Linux, FreeBSD or Solaris kernels and the proprietary graphics software.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Nvidia also provided but stopped supporting an obfuscated open-source driver that only supports two-dimensional hardware acceleration and ships with the X.Org distribution.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] The proprietary nature of Nvidia's drivers has generated dissatisfaction within free-software communities.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In a 2012 talk, Linus Torvalds gave a middle-finger gesture and criticized Nvidia's stance toward Linux.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Nvidia only provides x86/x64 and ARMv7-A versions of its proprietary driver; as a result, features like CUDA are unavailable on other platforms.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Some users claim that Nvidia's Linux drivers impose artificial restrictions, like limiting the number of monitors that can be used at the same time, but the company has not commented on these accusations.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] In 2014, with its Maxwell GPUs, Nvidia started to require firmware by it to unlock all features of its graphics cards.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] On May 12, 2022, Nvidia announced that it is opensourcing its GPU kernel modules.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] Support for Nvidia's firmware was implemented in nouveau in 2023, which allows proper power management and GPU reclocking for Turing and newer graphics card generations.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] On July 21, 2025, Nvidia announced to extend CUDA support to RISC-V.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p01] As of 2026, NVIDIA has over a 100 different open-source projects available on GitHub in different areas such as computer vision, networking, cybersecurity, AR/VR, Robotics, Generative AI etc.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] Nvidia GPUs are used in deep learning, and accelerated analytics due to Nvidia's CUDA software platform and API which allows programmers to utilize the higher number of cores present in GPUs to parallelize BLAS operations which are extensively used in machine learning algorithms.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] They were included in many Tesla, Inc. vehicles before Musk announced at Tesla Autonomy Day in 2019 that the company developed its own SoC and full self-driving computer now and would stop using Nvidia hardware for their vehicles.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] These GPUs are used by researchers, laboratories, tech companies and enterprise companies.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] In 2009, Nvidia was involved in what was called the "big bang" of deep learning, "as deep-learning neural networks were combined with Nvidia graphics processing units (GPUs)".
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] That year, the Google Brain team used Nvidia GPUs to create deep neural networks capable of machine learning, where Andrew Ng determined that GPUs could increase the speed of deep learning systems by about 100 times.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] DGX is a line of supercomputers by Nvidia.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] In April 2016, Nvidia produced the DGX-1 based on an 8 GPU cluster, to improve the ability of users to use deep learning by combining GPUs with integrated deep learning software.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] Nvidia gifted its first DGX-1 to OpenAI in August 2016 to help it train larger and more complex AI models with the capability of reducing processing time from six days to two hours.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] It also developed Nvidia Tesla K80 and P100 GPU-based virtual machines, which are available through Google Cloud, which Google installed in November 2016.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] Microsoft added GPU servers in a preview offering of its N series based on Nvidia's Tesla K80s, each containing 4992 processing cores.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] Later that year, AWS's P2 instance was produced using up to 16 Nvidia Tesla K80 GPUs.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] That month Nvidia also partnered with IBM to create a software kit that boosts the AI capabilities of Watson, called IBM PowerAI.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] Nvidia also offers its own Nvidia Deep Learning software development kit.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] In 2017, the GPUs were also brought online at the Riken Center for Advanced Intelligence Project for Fujitsu.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] The company's deep learning technology led to a boost in its 2017 earnings.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] In 2018, Nvidia researchers demonstrated imitation-learning techniques for industrial robots.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] They have created a system that, after a short revision and testing, can already be used to control the universal robots of the next generation.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] In addition to GPU manufacturing, Nvidia provides parallel processing capabilities to researchers and scientists that allow them to efficiently run high-performance applications.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] In 2020, Nvidia unveiled "Omniverse", a virtual environment designed for engineers.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] Nvidia also open-sourced Isaac Sim, which makes use of this Omniverse to train robots through simulations that mimic the physics of the robots and the real world.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] In 2024, Huang oriented Nvidia's focus towards humanoid robots and self-driving cars, which he expects to gain widespread adoption.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] In 2025, Nvidia announced Isaac GR00T N1, an open-source foundation model "designed to expedite the development and capabilities of humanoid robots".
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] Neura Robotics, 1X Technologies and Vention are among the first companies to use the model.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] NVIDIA has been involves in the automotive industry since introducing NVIDIA drive in CES 2015.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] In April 2021, NVIDIA announced "DRIVE Sim" - A simulation platform for autonomous vehicles based on the Omniverse platform, which according to NVIDIA brought high fidelity, and was much more physically accurate and fully repeatable which is required for V&V.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] In January 2026, NVIDIA announced Alpamayo, "family of open AI models, simulation tools and datasets designed to accelerate the next era of safe, reasoning‑based autonomous vehicle (AV) development.".
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] Nvidia's Inception Program was created to support startups making exceptional advances in the fields of artificial intelligence and data science.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] Award winners are announced at Nvidia's GTC Conference.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] In May 2017, the program had 1,300 companies.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] As of March 2018, there were 2,800 startups in the Inception Program.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] As of August 2021, the program has over 8,500 members in 90 countries, with cumulative funding of US$60 billion.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] Issues with the GeForce GTX 970's specifications were first brought up by users when they found out that the cards, while featuring 4 GB of memory, rarely accessed memory over the 3.5 GB boundary.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] The card's back-end hardware specifications, initially announced as being identical to those of the GeForce GTX 980, differed in the amount of L2 cache (1.75 MB versus 2 MB in the GeForce GTX 980) and the number of ROPs (56 versus 64 in the 980).
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] Additionally, it was revealed that the card was designed to access its memory as a 3.5 GB section, plus a 0.5 GB one, access to the latter being 7 times slower than the first one.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] The company then went on to promise a specific driver modification to alleviate the performance issues produced by the cutbacks suffered by the card.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] However, Nvidia later clarified that the promise had been a miscommunication and there would be no specific driver update for the GTX 970.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] Nvidia claimed that it would assist customers who wanted refunds in obtaining them.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] On February 26, 2015, Nvidia CEO Jensen Huang went on record in Nvidia's official blog to apologize for the incident.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] In February 2015 a class-action lawsuit alleging false advertising was filed against Nvidia and Gigabyte Technology in the United States District Court for the Northern District of California.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] Nvidia revealed that it is able to disable individual units, each containing 256 KB of L2 cache and 8 ROPs, without disabling whole memory controllers.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] This is used in the GeForce GTX 970, which therefore can be described as having 3.5 GB in its high speed segment on a 224-bit bus and 0.5 GB in a low speed segment on a 32-bit bus.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] On July 27, 2016, Nvidia agreed to a preliminary settlement of the U.S. class action lawsuit, offering a $30 refund on GTX 970 purchases.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] The agreed upon refund represents the portion of the cost of the storage and performance capabilities the consumers assumed they were obtaining when they purchased the card.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] The Nvidia GeForce Partner Program was a marketing program designed to provide partnering companies with benefits such as public relations support, video game bundling, and marketing development funds.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] The program proved to be controversial, with complaints about it possibly being an anti-competitive practice.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] First announced in a blog post on March 1, 2018, it was canceled on May 4, 2018.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] On December 10, 2020, Nvidia told YouTube tech reviewer Steven Walton of Hardware Unboxed that it would no longer supply him with GeForce Founders Edition graphics card review units.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] In a Twitter message, Hardware Unboxed said, "Nvidia have officially decided to ban us from receiving GeForce Founders Edition GPU review samples.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] Their reasoning is that we are focusing on rasterization instead of ray tracing.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] A number of technology reviewers came out strongly against Nvidia's move.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] Linus Sebastian, of Linus Tech Tips, titled the episode of his weekly WAN Show, "NVIDIA might ACTUALLY be EVIL..." and was highly critical of the company's move to dictate specific outcomes of technology reviews.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] The review site Gamers Nexus said it was, "Nvidia's latest decision to shoot both its feet: They've now made it so that any reviewers covering RT will become subject to scrutiny from untrusting viewers who will suspect subversion by the company.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] Two days later, Nvidia reversed its stance.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] Hardware Unboxed sent out a Twitter message, "I just received an email from Nvidia apologizing for the previous email & they've now walked everything back." On December 14, Hardware Unboxed released a video explaining the controversy from their viewpoint.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] In 2018, Nvidia's chips became popular for cryptomining, the process of obtaining crypto rewards in exchange for verifying transactions on distributed ledgers, the United States Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) said.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] However, the company failed to disclose that it was a "significant element" of its revenue growth from sales of chips designed for gaming, the SEC further added in a statement and charging order.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] Those omissions misled investors and analysts who were interested in understanding the impact of cryptomining on Nvidia's business, the SEC emphasized.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] Nvidia, which did not admit or deny the findings, has agreed to pay $5.5 million to settle civil charges, according to a statement made by the SEC in May 2022.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] On September 26, 2023, Nvidia's French offices were searched by the French Competition Authority.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] The raid, authorized by a judge, was part of an investigation into suspected anti-competitive practices in the graphics card sector.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] Nvidia has not publicly commented on the incident.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] In August 2025, Nvidia ordered suppliers to halt production of its H20 AI chip following Chinese government directives warning domestic companies against purchasing the processor due to security concerns.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] The company directed suppliers including Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company, Samsung Electronics, and Amkor Technology to suspend work on the China-focused processor.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] The H20 was developed in late 2023 specifically for the Chinese market to comply with U.S. export restrictions, featuring 96GB of HBM3 memory and 4.0 TB/s memory bandwidth-higher than the H100-but with significantly reduced computational power at 296 TFLOPs compared to the H100's 1979 TFLOPs.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] Despite lower raw performance, the H20 demonstrated over 20% faster performance than the H100 in large language model inference tasks due to architectural optimizations.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] Prior to the production halt, Nvidia had placed substantial orders for the H20, including 300,000 units from TSMC in July 2025, driven by strong demand from Chinese technology companies.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] Despite China's efforts to shape technical standards, still, American products and ecosystem retain strong appeal, raising government experts concern.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] CEO Jensen Huang denied allegations that the H20 contained security backdoors, stating the chips were designed solely for commercial use.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] The production suspension occurred as Nvidia was developing the B30A, a new chip based on its Blackwell architecture intended to succeed the H20 in the Chinese market.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] Despite criticism, the United States announced in 2026 that it would permit the export of newer H200 chips to China under specified conditions.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] The move was expected to stimulate market activity and U.S. influence.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] The Chinese market, estimated to be worth hundreds of billions and potentially trillions of U.S. dollars, presents significant profit opportunities for American firms, with revenues reinforcing leading positions.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] However, China quickly responded by imposing restrictions on certain foreign chips to be imported.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] China is leveraging the sanction to advance its domestic technology sector, while concerns have also emerged over possible fragmentation and reduced reinvestment in its own artificial intelligence development.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] China’s refusal to buy them could cost the company $30 billion.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] Nvidia has been involved in heavy data scraping for illegal AI model training.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] In 2024, internal conversations revealed that Nvidia was scraping large amounts of videos from YouTube without permission, and by circumventing protection measures.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] In January 2026, a court filing revealed that Nvidia developers contacted shadow library Anna's Archive to evaluate the use of pirated content for model training, which management gave green light for despite legality concerns from the site.
[src:tensorrt-llm/nvidia-p02] Nvidia denied the allegations and filed a motion to dismiss the lawsuit.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] In mathematics and digital signal processing, **quantization** is the process of mapping input values from a large set (often a continuous set) to output values in a (countable) smaller set, often with a finite number of elements.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Rounding and truncation are typical examples of quantization processes.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Quantization is involved to some degree in nearly all digital signal processing, as the process of representing a signal in digital form ordinarily involves rounding.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Quantization also forms the core of essentially all lossy compression algorithms.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] The difference between an input value and its quantized value (such as round-off error) is referred to as **quantization error**, **noise** or **distortion**.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] A device or algorithmic function that performs quantization is called a **quantizer**.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] An analog-to-digital converter is an example of a quantizer.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] For example, rounding a real number x to the nearest integer value forms a very basic type of quantizer – a *uniform* one.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] where the notation $\lfloor \ \rfloor$ denotes the floor function.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] (The notation $\lceil \ \rceil$ denotes the ceiling function).
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] The essential property of a quantizer is having a countable set of possible output values smaller than the set of possible input values.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] The members of the set of output values may have integer, rational, or real values.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] For simple rounding to the nearest integer, the step size $\Delta$ is equal to 1.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] With $\Delta =1$ or with $\Delta$ equal to any other integer value, this quantizer has real-valued inputs and integer-valued outputs.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] When the quantization step size (Δ) is small relative to the variation in the signal being quantized, it is relatively simple to show that the mean squared error produced by such a rounding operation will be approximately $\Delta ^{2}/12$ .
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Mean squared error is also called the quantization *noise power*.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Adding one bit to the quantizer halves the value of Δ, which reduces the noise power by the factor ⁠1/4⁠.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] This two-stage decomposition applies equally well to vector as well as scalar quantizers.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Because quantization is a many-to-few mapping, it is an inherently non-linear and irreversible process (i.e., because the same output value is shared by multiple input values, it is impossible, in general, to recover the exact input value when given only the output value).
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] The set of possible input values may be infinitely large, and may possibly be continuous and therefore uncountable (such as the set of all real numbers, or all real numbers within some limited range).
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] The set of possible output values may be finite or countably infinite.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] The input and output sets involved in quantization can be defined in a rather general way.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] For example, vector quantization is the application of quantization to multi-dimensional (vector-valued) input data.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] An analog-to-digital converter (ADC) can be modeled as two processes: sampling and quantization.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Sampling converts a time-varying voltage signal into a discrete-time signal, a sequence of real numbers.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Quantization replaces each real number with an approximation from a finite set of discrete values.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Most commonly, these discrete values are represented as fixed-point words.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Though any number of quantization levels is possible, common word lengths are 8-bit (256 levels), 16-bit (65,536 levels) and 24-bit (16.8 million levels).
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Quantizing a sequence of numbers produces a sequence of quantization errors, which is sometimes modeled as an additive random signal called **quantization noise** because of its stochastic behavior.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] The more levels a quantizer uses, the lower is its quantization noise power.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Most uniform quantizers for signed input data can be classified as being of one of two types: *mid-riser* and *mid-tread*.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] The terminology is based on what happens in the region around the value 0, and uses the analogy of viewing the input-output function of the quantizer as a stairway.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Mid-tread quantizers have a zero-valued reconstruction level (corresponding to a *tread* of a stairway), while mid-riser quantizers have a zero-valued classification threshold (corresponding to a *riser* of a stairway).
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Mid-tread quantization involves rounding.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] The formulas for mid-tread uniform quantization are provided in the previous section.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Mid-riser quantization involves truncation.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Note that mid-riser uniform quantizers do not have a zero output value – their minimum output magnitude is half the step size.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] In contrast, mid-tread quantizers do have a zero output level.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] For some applications, having a zero output signal representation may be a necessity.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] In general, a mid-riser or mid-tread quantizer may not actually be a *uniform* quantizer – i.e., the size of the quantizer's classification intervals may not all be the same, or the spacing between its possible output values may not all be the same.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] The distinguishing characteristic of a mid-riser quantizer is that it has a classification threshold value that is exactly zero, and the distinguishing characteristic of a mid-tread quantizer is that is it has a reconstruction value that is exactly zero.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] A **dead-zone quantizer** is a type of mid-tread quantizer with symmetric behavior around 0.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] The region around the zero output value of such a quantizer is referred to as the *dead zone* or *deadband*.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] The dead zone can sometimes serve the same purpose as a noise gate or squelch function.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Especially for compression applications, the dead-zone may be given a different width than that for the other steps.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] where the function $\operatorname {sgn}$ ( ) is the sign function (also known as the *signum* function).
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] where $r_{k}$ is a reconstruction offset value in the range of 0 to 1 as a fraction of the step size.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Ordinarily, $0\leq r_{k}\leq {\tfrac {1}{2}}$ when quantizing input data with a typical probability density function (PDF) that is symmetric around zero and reaches its peak value at zero (such as a Gaussian, Laplacian, or generalized Gaussian PDF).
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Although $r_{k}$ may depend on k in general and can be chosen to fulfill the optimality condition described below, it is often simply set to a constant, such as ${\tfrac {1}{2}}$ .
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] A very commonly used special case (e.g., the scheme typically used in financial accounting and elementary mathematics) is to set $w=\Delta$ and $r_{k}={\tfrac {1}{2}}$ for all k .
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] In this case, the dead-zone quantizer is also a uniform quantizer, since the central dead-zone of this quantizer has the same width as all of its other steps, and all of its reconstruction values are equally spaced as well.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] A common assumption for the analysis of quantization error is that it affects a signal processing system in a similar manner to that of additive white noise – having negligible correlation with the signal and an approximately flat power spectral density.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] The additive noise model is commonly used for the analysis of quantization error effects in digital filtering systems, and it can be very useful in such analysis.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] It has been shown to be a valid model in cases of high-resolution quantization (small $\Delta$ relative to the signal strength) with smooth PDFs.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Additive noise behavior is not always a valid assumption.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Quantization error (for quantizers defined as described here) is deterministically related to the signal and not entirely independent of it.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Thus, periodic signals can create periodic quantization noise.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] And in some cases, it can even cause limit cycles to appear in digital signal processing systems.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] One way to ensure effective independence of the quantization error from the source signal is to perform *dithered quantization* (sometimes with *noise shaping*), which involves adding random (or pseudo-random) noise to the signal prior to quantization.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] In the typical case, the original signal is much larger than one least significant bit (LSB).
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] When this is the case, the quantization error is not significantly correlated with the signal and has an approximately uniform distribution.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] When rounding is used to quantize, the quantization error has a mean of zero and the root mean square (RMS) value is the standard deviation of this distribution, given by $\scriptstyle {\frac {1}{\sqrt {12}}}\mathrm {LSB} \ \approx \ 0.289\,\mathrm {LSB}$ .
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] When truncation is used, the error has a non-zero mean of $\scriptstyle {\frac {1}{2}}\mathrm {LSB}$ and the RMS value is $\scriptstyle {\frac {1}{\sqrt {3}}}\mathrm {LSB}$ .
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Although rounding yields less RMS error than truncation, the difference is only due to the static (DC) term of $\scriptstyle {\frac {1}{2}}\mathrm {LSB}$ .
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] The RMS values of the AC error are exactly the same in both cases, so there is no special advantage of rounding over truncation in situations where the DC term of the error can be ignored (such as in AC-coupled systems).
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] In either case, the standard deviation, as a percentage of the full signal range, changes by a factor of 2 for each 1-bit change in the number of quantization bits.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] The potential signal-to-quantization-noise power ratio therefore changes by 4, or $\scriptstyle 10\cdot \log _{10}(4)$ , approximately 6 dB per bit.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] At lower amplitudes, the quantization error becomes dependent on the input signal, resulting in distortion.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] This distortion is created after the anti-aliasing filter, and if these distortions are above 1/2 the sample rate, they will alias back into the band of interest.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] In order to make the quantization error independent of the input signal, the signal is dithered by adding noise to the signal.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] This slightly reduces signal-to-noise ratio, but can completely eliminate the distortion.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Quantization noise is a model of quantization error introduced by quantization in the ADC.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] It is a rounding error between the analog input voltage to the ADC and the output digitized value.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] The noise is non-linear and signal-dependent.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] It can be modeled in several different ways.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] where Q is the number of quantization bits.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] The most common test signals that fulfill this are full amplitude triangle waves and sawtooth waves.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] For example, a 16-bit ADC has a maximum signal-to-quantization-noise ratio of 6.02 × 16 = 96.3 dB.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Here, the quantization noise is once again *assumed* to be uniformly distributed.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] When the input signal has a high amplitude and a wide frequency spectrum, this is the case.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] In this case a 16-bit ADC has a maximum signal-to-noise ratio of 98.09 dB.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] The 1.761 difference in signal-to-noise only occurs due to the signal being a full-scale sine wave instead of a triangle or sawtooth.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] For complex signals in high-resolution ADCs this is an accurate model.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] For low-resolution ADCs, low-level signals in high-resolution ADCs, and for simple waveforms the quantization noise is not uniformly distributed, making this model inaccurate.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] In these cases the quantization noise distribution is strongly affected by the exact amplitude of the signal.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] The calculations are relative to full-scale input.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] For smaller signals, the relative quantization distortion can be very large.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] To circumvent this issue, analog companding can be used, but this can introduce distortion.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Often, the design of a quantizer involves supporting only a limited range of possible output values and performing clipping to limit the output to this range whenever the input exceeds the supported range.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] The error introduced by this clipping is referred to as *overload* distortion.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Within the extreme limits of the supported range, the amount of spacing between the selectable output values of a quantizer is referred to as its *granularity*, and the error introduced by this spacing is referred to as *granular* distortion.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] It is common for the design of a quantizer to involve determining the proper balance between granular distortion and overload distortion.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] For a given supported number of possible output values, reducing the average granular distortion may involve increasing the average overload distortion, and vice versa.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] A technique for controlling the amplitude of the signal (or, equivalently, the quantization step size $\Delta$ ) to achieve the appropriate balance is the use of *automatic gain control* (AGC).
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] However, in some quantizer designs, the concepts of granular error and overload error may not apply (e.g., for a quantizer with a limited range of input data or with a countably infinite set of selectable output values).
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] These two stages together comprise the mathematical operation of $y=Q(x)$ .
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Entropy coding techniques can be applied to communicate the quantization indices from a source encoder that performs the classification stage to a decoder that performs the reconstruction stage.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] One way to do this is to associate each quantization index k with a binary codeword $c_{k}$ .
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] An important consideration is the number of bits used for each codeword, denoted here by $\mathrm {length} (c_{k})$ .
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] A key observation is that rate R depends on the decision boundaries $\{b_{k}\}_{k=1}^{M-1}$ and the codeword lengths $\{\mathrm {length} (c_{k})\}_{k=1}^{M}$ , whereas the distortion D depends on the decision boundaries $\{b_{k}\}_{k=1}^{M-1}$ and the reconstruction levels $\{y_{k}\}_{k=1}^{M}$ .
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Solving the unconstrained problem is equivalent to finding a point on the convex hull of the family of solutions to an equivalent constrained formulation of the problem.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] However, finding a solution – especially a closed-form solution – to any of these three problem formulations can be difficult.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Solutions that do not require multi-dimensional iterative optimization techniques have been published for only three PDFs: the uniform, exponential, and Laplacian distributions.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Iterative optimization approaches can be used to find solutions in other cases.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] This observation can be used to ease the analysis – given the set of $\{b_{k}\}_{k=1}^{M-1}$ values, the value of each $y_{k}$ can be optimized separately to minimize its contribution to the distortion D .
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] The use of this approximation can allow the entropy coding design problem to be separated from the design of the quantizer itself.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Modern entropy coding techniques such as arithmetic coding can achieve bit rates that are very close to the true entropy of a source, given a set of known (or adaptively estimated) probabilities $\{p_{k}\}_{k=1}^{M}$ .
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] In some designs, rather than optimizing for a particular number of classification regions M , the quantizer design problem may include optimization of the value of M as well.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] For some probabilistic source models, the best performance may be achieved when M approaches infinity.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] The indices produced by an M -level quantizer can be coded using a fixed-length code using $R=\lceil \log _{2}M\rceil$ bits/symbol.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] For example, when $M=$ 256 levels, the FLC bit rate R is 8 bits/symbol.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] For this reason, such a quantizer has sometimes been called an 8-bit quantizer.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] However, using an FLC eliminates the compression improvement that can be obtained by use of better entropy coding.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Assuming an FLC with M levels, the rate–distortion minimization problem can be reduced to distortion minimization alone.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] which places each reconstruction value at the centroid (conditional expected value) of its associated classification interval.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Lloyd's Method I algorithm, originally described in 1957, can be generalized in a straightforward way for application to vector data.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] This generalization results in the Linde–Buzo–Gray (LBG) or k-means classifier optimization methods.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Moreover, the technique can be further generalized in a straightforward way to also include an entropy constraint for vector data.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] The Lloyd–Max quantizer is actually a uniform quantizer when the input PDF is uniformly distributed over the range $[y_{1}-\Delta /2,~y_{M}+\Delta /2)$ .
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] However, for a source that does not have a uniform distribution, the minimum-distortion quantizer may not be a uniform quantizer.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] The property of 6 dB improvement in SQNR for each extra bit used in quantization is a well-known figure of merit.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] However, it must be used with care: this derivation is only for a uniform quantizer applied to a uniform source.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] For other source PDFs and other quantizer designs, the SQNR may be somewhat different from that predicted by 6 dB/bit, depending on the type of PDF, the type of source, the type of quantizer, and the bit rate range of operation.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] However, it is common to assume that for many sources, the slope of a quantizer SQNR function can be approximated as 6 dB/bit when operating at a sufficiently high bit rate.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] At asymptotically high bit rates, the 6 dB/bit approximation is supported for many source PDFs by rigorous theoretical analysis.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Moreover, the structure of the optimal scalar quantizer (in the rate–distortion sense) approaches that of a uniform quantizer under these conditions.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Many physical quantities are actually quantized by physical entities.
[src:tensorrt-llm/quantization-signal-processing] Examples of fields where this limitation applies include electronics (due to electrons), optics (due to photons), biology (due to DNA), physics (due to Planck limits) and chemistry (due to molecules).
[src:tensorrt-llm/tensorrt] In current Nvidia documentation, the TensorRT name is also used for a broader product family that includes the core TensorRT SDK, TensorRT-LLM, and TensorRT-RTX.
[src:tensorrt-llm/tensorrt] The core SDK is primarily a proprietary Nvidia product, although Nvidia also maintains Apache-licensed open-source TensorRT repositories and related companion projects.
[src:tensorrt-llm/tensorrt] TensorRT was available as part of Nvidia's deep learning software stack by 2017, when it was described as a high-performance inference engine for deploying trained neural networks on Nvidia GPUs.
[src:tensorrt-llm/tensorrt] In 2018, Google announced integration of Nvidia TensorRT with TensorFlow 1.7, describing TensorRT as a library that optimizes deep learning models for inference and creates a runtime for deployment on GPUs in production environments.
[src:tensorrt-llm/tensorrt] The core of TensorRT is a C++ library that takes a trained network, consisting of a network definition and trained parameters, and produces a highly optimized runtime engine for inference on Nvidia GPUs.
[src:tensorrt-llm/tensorrt] TensorRT provides both C++ and Python APIs, and models can either be expressed directly through its network definition API or imported through its ONNX parser.
[src:tensorrt-llm/tensorrt] According to Nvidia's documentation, TensorRT performs graph-level and kernel-level optimizations such as layer fusion and selection of efficient implementations for supported operations.
[src:tensorrt-llm/tensorrt] Current documentation also describes support for dynamic shapes, mixed-precision execution modes including FP32, FP16, BF16, FP8, and INT8, and specialized optimizations for transformer and large language model workloads.
[src:tensorrt-llm/tensorrt] TensorRT engines can be generated through the TensorRT APIs or with the *trtexec* command-line utility.
[src:tensorrt-llm/tensorrt] Nvidia's quick-start documentation describes deployment workflows based on ONNX conversion, runtime APIs, and direct engine deserialization for C++ and Python applications.
[src:tensorrt-llm/tensorrt] The licensing model around TensorRT is split between a proprietary core SDK and a set of open-source repositories and tools.
[src:tensorrt-llm/tensorrt] The packaged TensorRT software distributed by Nvidia is governed by the Nvidia Software License Agreement.
[src:tensorrt-llm/tensorrt] At the same time, Nvidia maintains a public TensorRT repository on GitHub under the Apache License 2.0.
[src:tensorrt-llm/tensorrt] Official TensorRT documentation also directs users to the TensorRT open-source software repository for quick-start code and samples.
[src:tensorrt-llm/tensorrt] The architecture documentation describes related tooling such as Polygraphy for debugging and constant folding, as well as ONNX-GraphSurgeon for modifying ONNX graphs before deployment with TensorRT.
[src:tensorrt-llm/tensorrt] TensorRT also supports a plugin mechanism for custom layers and unsupported operations.
[src:tensorrt-llm/tensorrt] Nvidia's current documentation groups several inference products under the TensorRT name.
[src:tensorrt-llm/tensorrt] In that documentation, the core SDK is distinguished as **TensorRT (Enterprise)**, while related offerings include TensorRT-LLM for large language model inference and TensorRT-RTX for consumer RTX GPUs.
[src:tensorrt-llm/tensorrt] According to Nvidia's product-family documentation, TensorRT-LLM supports multi-GPU and multi-node execution, in-flight batching, paged KV cacheing, and quantization methods such as FP8, INT8, and INT4 for higher-throughput model serving.
[src:tensorrt-llm/tensorrt] The TensorRT-LLM codebase is published on GitHub under the Apache License 2.0.
[src:tensorrt-llm/tensorrt] Because Nvidia documents TensorRT-LLM as a separate member of the TensorRT product family, it is typically treated as a related but distinct software project rather than as a single feature of the base TensorRT SDK.
